#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:3
msgid "Interviews - what to say"
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:5
msgid ""
"Such a great deal has been written about what to say in a job interview "
"that you might doubt whether it's worth adding any more."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:7
msgid ""
"Be warned that a lot of what you will find is really bad advice, and some"
" of it is very thoughtlessly given."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:11
msgid "Being prepared"
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:14
msgid "Always tell the truth"
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:17
msgid "Whatever you say needs to be true."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:21
msgid ""
"Nothing will end a candidate's chances sooner than the suspicion that "
"they have a casual relationship with the truth."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:23
msgid ""
"Don't blur reality, and don't mislead. Don't make things up. Don't "
"embellish or exaggerate."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:25
msgid ""
"That doesn't mean you have to say everything that is true. Candidates "
"often reveal more than they need to."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:27
msgid ""
"Also, as every adult understands, when it comes anything but the simplest"
" of cases no-one is in sole possession of the one and only truth. Even "
"reasonable and fair-minded people on opposite sides of an issue can "
"honestly see it in different ways."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:29
msgid ""
"All this makes it really important to adopt a thoughtful approach to what"
" you are going to say, which means thinking ahead to what you are going "
"to be asked and to your responses."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:33
msgid "Speaking about negative things"
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:35
msgid ""
"A real challenge is how to speak about negative or problematic things. Be"
" aware that whatever you say reflects on you more than it does about the "
"people or things you talk about -- even if that's not really fair."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:39
msgid ""
"One of the worst things you can possibly do is complain about existing or"
" former colleagues or criticise other people."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:41
msgid ""
"When an interviewer hears about a candidate's disagreeable colleague, "
"they will wonder: \"What's the other side of this story?\" A candidate "
"who complains about more than one problematic work relationship "
"inevitably makes the interviewer think: \"What is the common factor "
"here?\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:43
msgid ""
"The more certain you are about the failings of others, the more burning "
"your sense of something that was done wrong, the more effort you must "
"take to avoid talking about those things in the wrong ways. Not only is "
"there a risk that what you say will be interpreted as revealing something"
" about *you*, there is a real chance that once you start saying it you'll"
" be carried along by your feelings and will find you've said more than "
"you intended."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:47
msgid "Positive framing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:49
msgid ""
"Frame dissatisfaction in positive terms, about the values you hold and "
"about what you hope to find next: opportunities, advancement, challenge, "
"expert leadership, and so on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:51
msgid ""
"Don't say that your current workplace is chaotic and badly-managed. Say: "
"\"I value planning, and I want to find myself working in a more "
"structured environment.\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:53
msgid ""
"Don't say that your work is boring and the challenges unambitious. Say: "
"\"I want to be challenged more, and work on more exciting projects.\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:55
msgid ""
"Don't say that effort and achievement are not properly recognised where "
"you are now. Say: \"It's really important to me to work in a context with"
" an effective framework of recognition and reward, and I feel that could "
"be improved at my current employer.\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:57
msgid ""
"Don't say: \"Management has no idea how to market our product, and it's "
"failing.\" Say: \"We have an excellent product that I am really proud of "
"and believe in, but I am frustrated that we don't have more success with "
"it. I think we could take a different approach to marketing.\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:59
msgid ""
"You'll notice that each of those statements hints at or even clearly "
"acknowledges a problem, but doesn't criticise anyone or or complain. In "
"each case, it makes it about *you*, and what *you* care about."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:61
msgid ""
"All of the examples show that there is something you're not satisfied "
"with (*e.g.* \"I'm frustrated that...\"). It's fine to show that you have"
" a critical attitude (\"I feel that could be improved\")."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:63
msgid ""
"A positive judgement (\"We have an excellent product\") makes any "
"negative sentiments seem more nuanced and credible."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:65
msgid ""
"When you say \"I am frustrated/disappointed/unhappy\" you are "
"acknowledging that you have a part in what it is, and that you are a "
"human being with their own perspective and feelings. You're not judging "
"it from a distance or suggesting that it's all up to other people."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:67
msgid ""
"And crucially, in every case above, you offer a positive way forward - no"
" problem is stated without a constructive idea of what would be better."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:71
msgid "Don't say more than you need to"
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:75
msgid "It shows confidence to stop when it's time to stop."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:77
msgid ""
"Know when to shut up! It's hard to do that when you are nervous, but when"
" you have said the thing you want to say, *that's enough*. If they want "
"to know more, they will say so, and it's always better to leave people "
"wanting more than waiting impatiently for you to stop talking."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:79
msgid ""
"If you're in any doubt, \"Is there any aspect of that you'd like to know "
"more about?\" signals that there *is* more, and that you care about what "
"*they* are interested in."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:81
msgid ""
"The other advantage of not saying more than you need to is that *you are "
"less likely to say something that you shouldn't*, that gives away too "
"much. If you're already nervous, the chances are that you will do exactly"
" that. You will add a qualification, introduce a doubt, reveal a "
"weakness, undermine something you already said."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:83
msgid ""
"Adding more weakens what you've said so far; it rarely reinforces it or "
"adds clarity. It makes it sound as though you didn't say the right things"
" in the first place, or didn't quite believe in them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:87
msgid "Uncertain territory"
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:89
msgid ""
"The time you are most likely to let yourself down by saying more than you"
" should is when you are not really sure of the answer. That's when people"
" tend to give vague, unfocused answers, and add more in the hope that the"
" next thing that comes out of their mouth will magically bring the topic "
"to a crisp conclusion - which it never does."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:91
msgid ""
"It's especially a risk to say too much when you are being asked questions"
" that ask about things that you feel *ambivalent* about (even more so "
"than the ones you feel negative about)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:93
msgid ""
"It's especially noticeable when a candidate is asked about what they "
"really want, or what they are really looking for -- such questions can "
"unlock a candidate's ambivalence, and they will reveal all kinds of "
"things that had they only thought more carefully they would have wisely "
"kept to themselves."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:95
msgid ""
"If the territory is in any way risky, or you aren't certain how you want "
"to talk about it, *keep what you say to a minimum*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:99
msgid "The questions you want them to ask you"
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:101
msgid ""
"There must be some questions you hope they ask, or topics you hope they "
"will bring up, because you know that this represents a chance for you to "
"shine."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:103
msgid ""
"What are those questions? Don't just hope that you'll be asked: make a "
"point of bringing them up if the interviewer doesn't."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:107
msgid "Do you have any questions for me?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:109
msgid ""
"You're almost certainly going to be asked if you have any questions: "
"another thing to think about in advance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:113
msgid ""
"A good one in fact is: \"I'm a bit surprised you didn't you ask me about "
"<a topic you were hoping they would bring up> -- did you want to hear "
"anything about that?\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:115
msgid ""
"Make your questions genuine questions. Work out what *you* want to know "
"about the company or the job. Don't worry that your question might seem "
"naïve or unimpressive."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:117
msgid ""
"You'll find a lot of advice offered about what questions to ask. Some of "
"it's good advice - but a question you are genuinely interested in is "
"worth much more. There are no off-the-shelf questions that magically "
"signal a candidate's excellence."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:121
msgid "Know exactly what you're going to say"
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:123
msgid ""
"It's often not easy to say the right thing on the spur of the moment. For"
" each question where you know you'll need to be careful about how you "
"tell the truth as you see it, for each tricky topic that could come up, "
"for everything that you feel ambivalent about, each question you hope "
"they will ask: decide in advance what exactly you're going to say, and "
"**have it written down**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:127
msgid "Avoid the temptation of saying more than you should."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:129
msgid ""
"Writing these things down is crucial; each one is one more thing you "
"don't have to think about on the spot."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:131
msgid ""
"There are always going to be surprises in interviews, but you can help "
"yourself immensely by reducing their number through good preparation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:135
msgid "Say specific and concrete things"
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:137
msgid ""
"In everything you say, be specific and concrete. It gives what you say "
"edge and detail that make it believable. It's hard to grasp generic "
"things."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:139
msgid ""
"Be specific about *where and when*. For example, if you're talking about "
"something you did, it helps to say \"When I was at xxx, I ...\". Now the "
"interviewer can picture you at xxx (university, this this or that "
"employer), working on whatever it was. Or: \"In 2014, I ...\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:141
msgid ""
"Be specific about *whom*. Not some vague \"they\"; \"my manager\", \"the "
"CEO\", \"my colleague Jane\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:143
msgid ""
"*Name* things. \"Postgres\", rather than \"the database\". \"django "
"CMS\", rather than \"our web CMS\". \"I used Numpy for the xxx and Pandas"
" for the yyy.\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:145
msgid ""
"Use *numbers*. \"I had two other people in my team\", rather than \"I led"
" a small team\". Don't be embarrassed that the numbers are small, or "
"imagine that they aren't impressive enough (candidates often feel that "
"they should draw a kind of veil over small things by being more general "
"about them -- but an interviewer will notice that)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../interview-success-what-to-say.rst:147
msgid ""
"Being specific and concrete are ways of bringing clarity to what you say."
" Every time you are clear, you add trust and believability."
msgstr ""

